# Docs sync

Tenantly is documentation-driven. Code and docs ship in the same change.

## Rule

If your change touches any of the following, update the matching doc in the **same PR**:

| What changed | Doc to update |
|---|---|
| DB schema (table/column/enum) | `docs/06-database/entities.md` + write a migration |
| RLS policy | `docs/05-backend/rls-patterns.md` + `docs/06-database/multi-tenancy.md` |
| Env var | `docs/09-operations/environment-variables.md` |
| Webhook integration | `docs/05-backend/webhooks-and-integrations.md` |
| Background job | `docs/05-backend/background-jobs.md` |
| Pricing tier / capability | `docs/01-business/pricing-and-subscriptions.md` + `core/billing/capabilities.ts` |
| Architecture decision | new ADR in `docs/03-architecture/adr/` |
| User flow | matching file in `docs/07-flows/` |
| Tech stack version bump (major) | `docs/03-architecture/tech-stack.md` |
| Any new feature | `docs/02-product/features.md` (move from "later" → "shipped") |

## Format

- ADRs use the standard format (Status / Context / Decision / Consequences).
- Flow docs use Mermaid sequence diagrams.
- Schema docs include SQL.
- Always link related docs at the bottom.

## Don't

- Don't write code that contradicts a doc without first updating the doc.
- Don't merge a "TODO: docs" PR. Either include them or split the PR.
- Don't duplicate content across docs — link instead.

## When the doc is wrong

Fix it. That's also a defect. The doc is the contract.

## When in doubt

Search `docs/` first. If the answer isn't there, write it down — that knowledge is now in the agent's context too.
